author: quiyo2

description.text: Reduced case width and length, board is now a snug fit. Also removed centre supports all intended to unblock pin holes when used on a Mini Breadboard. Fits a nano with pins straight down and no ICSP header pins fitted.

print_settings.Notes:: High infill would be good, but you need small layers for the best results, and that means it would take forever on high infill.

description.text: I've found that on my quest to create the cheapest possible fidget spinner without much quality loss, printed bearings are not that bad, and 2ROBOTGUY's designs are the only ones that work well. So I found a ball bearing that works well, (still experimenting with this https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:53451 and this https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2333792) scaled it up as far as I could, and stuck it in the center of the two of his designs that I use. They spin really good and I can do this to any design you want, just post a link to it in the comments.

Printer:

FlashForge Creator Pro

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.05 mm

Infill:

Doesn't Matter

Notes:

High infill would be good, but you need small layers for the best results, and that means it would take forever on high infill.
Add bearings or pennies and start spinning!

"I found a ball bearing that works well, (still experimenting with this https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:53451 and this https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2333792) scaled it up as far as I could, and stuck it in the center of the two of his designs that I use."

Model rocket launch pad inspired by this one.

Don't forget to add a metal disc to protect the launch pad from the flames.

Add

  • 1 M4 hex head bolt with a wing nut and washer to adjust the angle of the rod.

Doesn't Matter

No

0.15mm

20%

Notes:

Legs and base printed in ColorFabb nGen, but any basic filament should do. Print the base upside down.
The rod holder prints best sideways for maximum stability (see screenshot), I've used ColorFabb XT (PETG) to give it enough strength and you might want to use a higher infill and 3 perimeters.
The rod holder has a pretty snug fit in the base, so you might want to sand it down a little if your printer leaves little blobs or other artefacts.

title: bottom plate for parrot ar drone 2

description.text:
print your own bottom plate for the parrot ar drone 2.
this will protect the mainboard an electronics in case of hard landings or crashs on rough terrain. and with a little creativity it looks awesome. this version is meant to be glued either to the existing bottomplate or to the frame itself replacing the original bottomplate. keeping the original bottom plastic film seals the electonics from wetness, which isnt a bad thing.
of course you can drill some small holes in the plate and use it with an existing bottom-plate-screw-mod. in the pictures i printed 2 plates, the white one solid, and the black one with left out parts for my logo. the last pic is a photoshopped dramatisation of waht i hope it looks like after i installed some led's inside. depending on your print, it might be neccessary to make the hole for the groundcam a little bit wider.

print_settings.Notes:: I used a brim, not a raft, although either should be fine, but if your setup is good enough print it without anything as it will be less to tidy after.

description.text:
This snowflake fidget spinner is designed for a 608 bearing (grease removed) - 22mm by 7mm, and 10mm ball bearings. Degrease by removing the retaining rings and washing it in acetone, or similar, then drying and replacing the rings. There are plenty of guides out there for this.

You should be able to push the bearing into the centre ring by leaning into it on a table. Once you get the bearing in a little turn it over to push the spinner down the rest of the way onto the bearing (it's just easier on the hands). The ball bearings can be tapped in with a hammer (tap it, don't whack it), or pressed in with a vice. I intended to push them through until there was 1.5mm sticking out both sides of the spinner but ended up pushing it to be flush on one side so that it could spin on the cap on a flat surface. The balance is fine either way.

Printer:

Tevo Tarantula

Supports:

No

Notes:

I used a brim, not a raft, although either should be fine, but if your setup is good enough print it without anything as it will be less to tidy after.

A small screwdriver can be used if you get out any stringing inside the design. I used PLA, slightly too warm, and had to clean out some tags and strings.

Use a Dremel sanding cylinder or grinding stone if you need to tidy up the bearing/ball rings.

Holes for Batterystraps have to be widened, added foam so the battery wont get scratched,
Receiver relocated to where battery was at.

title: Rimless Aquarium Fan Mount - PC Case Fan

description.text:
Aquarium Fan Mount

A bracket for mounting a computer case fan to a rimless aquarium.

Inspired by devid89's aquarium fan mount, I designed a similar model that can be adapted to different sized fans and has an adjustable fan angle.

This design accomodates common sizes of case fans (80, 92, 120, 140) with no modification and can be modified to accomodate fans of varying thicknesses. The OpenSCAD files are hosted on github. Pull requests are welcome!

Instructions:

The files should work as-is for 5mm thick glass and a 25mm thick fan.

  • In AquariumFanMount-Clip.scad set glass_thickness to the desired thickness
  • In AquariumFanMount-Fan.scad set depth to the thickness of your fan

Required Hardware:

  • 2 - M4x15mm stainless steel or nylon screws (holds the clip and mount together)
  • 2 - M4x40mm stainless steel or nylon screws (holds the fan in the mount)
  • 4 - M4 stainless steel or nylon nuts
  • 1 - Threadlock (optional)

Control:

If you are looking for an easy way to control the fan Joey (aka "The King of DIY") has a video on how to build a temperature controller which could be used to control the fan(s)

Performance:

I'm using the pictured 120mm fan on my IM Fusion 20 (with the screen top on) and I am very happy with how this setup performs. I'm using a microcontroller to control the fan and my temperatures are very stable. I've seen it drop the temperature by 2-3 degrees Fahrenheit. I'd recommend trying something like this to help keep temps down or add some extra stability.

Evaporation:

A downside of running a fan for cooling is that it will cause more evaporation than normal. This makes having an Auto Top Off like these pretty important on saltwater tanks to ensure stable salinity. I haven't noticed a huge increase in top off water consumption but your mileage may vary. If you're looking for an inexpensive ATO check out this video from Joey. I've been running an ATO similar to this on a small freshwater tank and it works great. If you need a way of mounting your float switches check out my bracket design here.

Printer:

Sunhokey Prusa i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

20%

title: Raspberry Pi case top for Aidafruit PiTFT 2.8 inch touchscreen display

description.text:
This is a top that replaces the top for another Raspberry Pi case, thing:101837. I included the bottom here for completeness but I did not make any changes to it.  
The top has a hole for the 2.8 TFT display and space for the 4 optional buttons. There is a lip on the bottom fits around the board and it snaps in. So the GPIO connect actually becomes the connection between the top and the bottom of the case.   
Combined with a mini wireless keyboard, a wifi dongle and power supply it makes a nice little self contained RaspberryPi computer that can travel well in a backpack, etc.

title: The Best Damn Prusa i3 MK2 Bed Camera Mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
As many San Francisco Bay Arean makers know, we reach Ikea demo-display levels of usability with our tiny living spaces. It’s sometimes tough finding space to build stuff and still have more than a hammock strung between two burning man art cars to sleep on.

For me, the perfect spot to locate my first printer was the closet because:

  1. it was relatively draft-free (needed for ABS)
  2. I could leave the light on for time-lapse prints without annoying anyone
  3. being surrounded by clothes it really dampens the screeching from these incessant electrical banshees
  4. and the small chest-o’drawers in there just collected random coins, lint, and occasional fuses or bulbs lifted from my Pick-Your-Part that I'd emptied from my pockets at the end of the day anyway #amiright ???

But since upgrading from my quaint Printrbot Simple Metal 1403, my Original Prusa i3 MK2 is a veritable behemoth by comparison. It hangs off the end of the dresser so gets a corresponding larger share of snags, bumps, and bruises from being right in the middle of a very active area (the closet is home to my daily-used Dyson V6, broom, ironing board, clothes, shoes, Plex Media Server, etc). Because of this, I've broken the bed camera mount of 3 separate designs on it, including JPgxuAHFR22RQo's and cocoknight’s. This afternoon I’d had enough…

<POPEYE>
      That's all I can stans — I CAN'T STANS NO MO !
</POPEYE>

 

Ladies and gents, without further adieu I give you:

The Best Damn Prusa i3 MK2 Bed Camera Mount !

Nitty Gritty:

  • Doesn't snap in two as if it were crafted from paper mâché like every other lightweight bed mount design I've tried
  • Minimal weight (only 5g for this part when printed in ABS, ~6g for PETG or PLA)
  • As close and tall as possible to the bed while still not interfering with the extruder stepper motor during homing — no more viewing your timelapse knife-edge right at the bed
  • Left-mounted, where it gosh-darn ought'be ! With luc_e's over-engineered [4x M3 screws and nuts to hold in an RPi ? Really ? :] but sweet as August corn, Original Prusa MK2 style Octopi cover that mounts the RPi perfectly over the MK2’s MiniRAMBo enclosure, and along with Adafruit's 24" RPi camera CSI ribbon extension, allows the ribbon to slide along under the MK2's aluminum Z frame. I'm even powering the RPi from 5v from a spare endstop pin off the Mini RAMBo - who has 3hrs to same-day Amazon' yet another USB charger ?
  • No metal fasteners needed (the MK2 comes with an extra 12mm M3 screw to replace the stock 10mm one as part of the kit ;)
  • Part of its magic is its infill layout and settings (detailed below) but since I know what printer you're using, I've even included gcode for the uninitiated among us (you know who you are ;)
  • It’s Skookum as Frig !

Enjoy !

-=dave

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

200 microns

Infill:

11%

Notes:

Slice with Slic3rPE with following adjustments:

  • Original Prusa i3 MK2 Colorprint printer profile settings
  • 0.20mm NORMAL print profile settings
  • Solid top/bottom layers: 4/3
  • Seam position: rear
  • Fill density: 11%
  • Fill pattern: Grid
  • Combine infil every: 2
  • Solid infill every: 25
  • Fill angle: 0
  • Solid infill threshold area: 46
  • Print !

Gcode for ABS (tested), PETG, and PLA (untested) included for you lazy geniuses !

comments.text: Hi - I just tossed the ABS gcode over to Octoprint and immediately heard the fans spinning up differently than I'm used to, so I cracked open the file and find the warmup procedure you are using very interesting.  Never seen anything like that before.  Are you bringing the bed/extruder temperature up in stages like that to try to minimize the amount of time the PINDA probe spends soaking in heat?
comments.author: hberg32

comments.text: "The probe just missed high by a mile"
comments.author: hberg32

comments.text: Meaning the pinda was still a little warm from the last print and triggered way too high - so instead of extruding onto the bed the printer was waving the hotend around in mid-air.  I raised the gantry, let the pinda cool to room temperature and the next attempt worked just fine.
comments.author: fiveangle

comments.text: Yes, it's to help cool the PINDA closer to ambient.  My custom GCODE is designed to move the gantry up away from the bed and turn the part cooling fan on for a bit while the HE heats up.  It sounds like it may not be enough time to cool the PINDA if it is ran immediately after a print that ends right near the bed and uses an elevated bed temp.
comments.author: hberg32

comments.text: Works well, and is a great training kit to teach someone how to build a folder. I would suggest a few slight modifications. First, make the spring a bit beefier, it deforms too easily, fixed that by pushing a small piece of foam under the tab to help it return to lock position. Secondly, notch the top handle slightly so that you can get your thumbnail on the lock to push it down. Most knives are indented there to allow the lock to be accessed. This is similar to a liner lock spring setup, which might also make a nice modification. Nice job! A bit of tweaking and it works and looks good!

I designed this to be able to set the 3ds xl into the charging dock and have it immediately begin charging. Works everytime for mine.

A few notes:
-Tolerances are tight for the width of the device because they have to be for alignment. Your device will not fit if you have a case and it may or may not damage a skin if you have one.

-Because it is 3d printed it is a little light. Use two hands or drill 1" holes in the bottom and super glue a whole mess of weights until it stays. I just use two hands.

-Also, mine is shorter. I thought it would look nice to have some of the 3DS sticking out of the front. It didn't. If this goofs the alignment let me know and I will fix and reupload but with the way it was modeled it should be fine.

-The charging cord is inserted in the bottom and fed out the back. I tried to make it tall enough to avoid unnecessary strain on the cable and it was enough on mine. If it's not on yours be smart and either change the model or cut it out more with a Dremel. Some pressure will be required to insert it into the bottom. This ensures that the charger doesn't get pushed out the bottom when you set your 3DS in. Be gentle and use an Allen wrench or something to push it flush with the bottom.

-There is a tiny logo that I painstakingly traced. Appreciate it. Unfortunately, it doesn't show very well. If I ever print it again I will probably put it loud and proud on the side.

-Hope you guys like it. This is my first print uploaded but not the first time I have printed my own designs.

UPDATE: new models with improved border between Godswood and Downtown that does not split any trees. Also reinforced a tree

The spawn island on Minecraft seed 107038380838084 (from https://youtu.be/JFHGiv6qeX8 ) with a village I created on it. You don't even need support material to make it, it still looks good.

You can print all of it at once, or in three sections like there are provided

Fun facts:

1) the library and the large houses were made first to cover little ponds you can easily fall into.
2) like all naturally spawning villages, there is exactly one four way intersection with a well in it
3) Unlike naturally spawning villages, this is completely on the island, and has bridges instead of piers. Also has two smithies, and only superflat villages can have two natural smithies. The farms are also one block higher than villagers would place them, but it makes them more visible on a single-color model.
4) the small houses with roof access are strategically placed as lookouts
5) The beach houses next to the woods (on the same street as the large house and butcher's shop) were placed there as an extension to a road and bring the door count to 21, the minimum to spawn an iron golem (though you need 60 doors to breed enough villagers to spawn iron golems)
6) I made it in creative, copied the world to modify it for 3D printing and remade it in survival
7) you can walk onto a farm, on the roof of the large house, on the roof of the library and on top of the well. That opens up the possibility of parkour.
8) the roofs of the huts (flat vs dome) are also more parkour-friendly. Such as one block down has a dome roof and one block higher has a flat roof.
9) The island is shaped almost like a reverse Australia, complete with a little Tasmania and a Papa New Guinea
10) The small bridge was trickier to design with the minimum 3 block clearance for boats to pass and dismount underneath, whereas the larger bridge was not as necessary and taller. I made the latter because I can
11) In the original creative mode world, the small bridge has a flatter path, and I raised it up a block to put little lines of blocks underneath it to assists its printing without support material. The taller bridge has the lines without affecting clearance underneath enough to matter.
12) not a single tree was cut down to make way for the houses
13) many trees are reinforced. The isolated large tree attaches itself to the houses next to it, whereas some tree trunks have a plus shape.

description.text:
The idea was I wanted as much printing area as possible for my FLSun Mini Kossel, but also have a heated bed with insulation and glass top (eventually with PEI as well). The mounting holes in the bed took up more space than I wanted and could only use three of them which made the bed uneven and flexible. I couldn't put the glass bed flush without removing them. The bed now lays flat on the base with no springs.

Coming soon:

  • taller versions added to support bed screws head clearance and help with warping when heating and cooling the brackets from the bed.

Needed Items:

  • 12 M4x14mm Hex Socket Cap Head screws (http://r.ebay.com/l3QTm3)
  • 12 M4 2020 CNC nuts (http://r.ebay.com/7efBo9)
  • 12 M4 washers (optional). stops the screws heads from digging in the bracket mounts
  • 6 M4 x 20 Hex Socket Cap Head screws (http://r.ebay.com/l3QTm3)
  • 6 M4 square nuts (I used what came with FLSun)

  • 3 M4x30mm Hex Socket Cap Head screws (http://r.ebay.com/l3QTm3)

  • 6 M3x10mm or M3x12mm (optional) - used on taller version; meant to hold bed in place

I provided many different options.

  • MiniKossel_bedbracket_press_v5.stl (optional). Used to pushed the brackets to tighten the bed; also helps even the bed out.
  • MiniKossel_bedbracket_clamp_bedonly_v2.stl - if using just the 220m bed
  • MiniKossel_bedbracket_clamp_220BedCorkGlass_v5.stl - if you have cork and glass top for the bed
  • MiniKossel_bedbracket_clamp_220BedCork_v5.stl - just the cork and bed clamp; may have to flip upside down (when mounting) depending on cork thickness
  • MiniKossel_bedbracket_bracket_front_v3.stl - print two (for the front)
  • MiniKossel_bedbracket_bracket_v3.stl (for the back)

title: Heavy Duty - Enclosed Bearing - Tri Fidget Spinner Toy

description.text:
After dropping and breaking several 3D printed Tri Fidget Spinner Toys, I knocked up this design which has the following features:

  • Uses 4 x standard 608 bearings.
  • Bearings are enclosed within the 2 half shells, so no stress on the plastic and bearings can not fall out.
  • 5mm bearing walls and 9mm total shell height for additional strength.
  • Bearings fit easily into the shells, so not force or clamping required.
  • If printed with ABS, it can survive several meter drops onto concrete without cracking/dropping bearings.
  • ABS shells can be glued with liquid ABS or super glue.

Printed with ABS, 0.5mm nozzle, 0.3mm layer height.

Designed in Sketchup Make, design file included.

I found the +3% version fitted perfectly when printing with ABS (bearings can be finger pressed into the shells).

Please let me know if anyone tries this design with PLA, I am guessing it would still crack if dropped onto concrete from several meters?

title: Octopi Adapter Plate MK2S and MK3

description.text:
While looking for an Octopi case for my raspberry pi 2 on my new Prusa i3 MK2S printer, I quickly realized there were lots of great choices but all were created before MK2S was released.

I was already set on hofftari's excellent case https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1325370 and had printed it before I realized MK2S changed the cable setup!

So searching around I found jackrenter's adapter plate https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2265551, however I wanted to flip the Pi to the outside edge of the Prusa to give a more natural path for the raspi's camera cable and more properly orient the USB cables.

Thus this adapter plate was born to flip over the case and align with the right side of the Prusa frame. This works on MK2, MK2S and MK3 so long as you aren't using these holes for the MMU.

This is a much more natural position for the Pi case. The ribbon cable for the pi camera nicely routes out the right side and down below the chassis without interfering with the print area or prusa cables. The USB cable also routes nicely and leave the micros SD card up at the top for easy access.

Case is nicely flush on top and right side of frame.

title: Springy Spool Hub (customizable)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Makerbot seems to be incapable of fixing the integrated openscad customizer. It's down for a long time now. You can still edit the design on your own computer. Download openscad and open the .scad file in the editor to modify the hub.

Design Intent

I was looking for a spool hub that could fit different size spools while, other than e.g. stepped hubs, maintaining the same width of the spool when mounted. I also wanted it to lock reliably into the spool, print quickly and with little material.
As this thing was constructed in openSCAD you can adapt it to your requirements in Customizer.

The clamp in the picture is this one: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2356396.

Customizing

If you adapt the hub to your spool sizes make the diameter bigger than the maximum hole size you want it to fit. As a rule of thumb about 5-10% plus. This guarantees that the springs have enough tension to lock it in.

Learnings

  • The design shows that even PLA can be used to create quite robust springs as long as they are long, relatively thin and printed with perimeters only.
  • It was quite a trigonometry challenge to calculate the position of the root fillet in the back of the vane :-).

FAQ - What does "customizable" mean?

Customizable means that you can modify the model by changing the parameters that define it. In case of this thing you can modify for example its main diameter the diameter of its center bore and much more just by changing the respective numbers in the Customizer App.
The beautiful thing with parametric models is that you can adapt something to your needs without understanding the underlying design principles. Give it a try by clicking "Open in Customizer".

Revisions

rev2: fixed missing path in vane profile
rev3: exported root fillet parameter
rev4: added optional bearing seat

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Clone

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

variable

Infill:

none

Notes:

The design prints well with rigid PLA. Actually I found PLA optimal for this. PETG is to malleable.

Make sure to slice the vanes as 100% perimeters/walls if they have infill / top / bottom layers they are not flexible. By default they are 4x extrusion width wide so the correct setting would be 2 perimeters/walls.

I print without part cooling for optimal layer adhesion and to have a somewhat malleable part for pressing in the bearing.

Happy Printing.

Installing the bearing

If you print a type of this thing with a bearing. Press in the bearing right after the print finishes and it is still slightly soft.

description.text:
<Update: 12/30/2017>
Changed description to include MK3 since it fits in the same holes on the MK3 frame so long as you don't have the Multi-Material Upgrade installed.

<Update: 9/18/2017>
Thanks to jhans1 feedback in the comments, this case is confirmed to work for both Raspberry Pi 2 & Raspberry Pi 3.

This is a remix of hofftari's excellent Rasperry Pi 2 Octopi case for the Prusa i3 MK2. After I remixed another adapter to make his case fit my new MK2S, I realized that I could easily adapt his original case to include my adapter as an all-in-one solution. Thus I remixed my own adapter plate (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2334079) and hofftari's case (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1325370) to come up with this new design.

This also eliminated the M3 bolt that was originally located inside the lid and dangerously close to the Pi's GPIO pins.

description.text:
Hi all... The idea is based on the expensive LulzBot TAZ 6 and the already famous Wilson II by mrice https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1086101. she's a complete redesign for 300x300x320 build volume using 2020 aluminium, 10mm shaft, with bowden extruder and make her stiffer in some area. Bare in mind that I'm not an engineer, that's why I share this design, In hope the community will help share their thoughts as to improve the design furthermore.

UPDATE. Well, it's finally done and she's working flawlessly, I've uploaded the STL's, BOM, photos and marlin 1.1.3 configuration. Instruction will soon follow. Thank you very much.

Here's a video of it test printing @50mm/s

After you build one, don't forget to equalize the height of the right and left Z axis by turning the motor coupling manually.

Printer:

Any 200x200x200 printer

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

30%

Notes:
  • Use 3 perimeters (top, bottom, shell)
  • 30% infill minimum
  • "..._Print_2" means print it twice
  • File one side of the 2020 corner joint bracket. See pic

2020 Aluminium extrusion:

Make sure the slot opening is 6mm or above

  • 4 x 430mm (for X axis)
  • 2 x 515mm (for Y axis) or 520mm
  • 4 x 500mm (for Z axis)
10mm hardened steel smooth rod:
  • 2 x 470mm (for X axis)
  • 2 x 515mm (for Y axis) or 520mm
  • 2 x 450mm (for Z axis)
  • 1 x 8mm smooth rod x 150mm for spool holder or use this spool holder
Electronics:
  • 1 x Endstop switch (only requires 2)
  • 5 x Nema17 stepper motor
  • 1 x MK3 Aluminium 300x300x3mm heatbed
  • 1 x MKS Gen-L V1.0
  • 1 x MKS TFT32 Touch Screen or Reprap 2004 LCD module
  • 2 x A4988 stepper driver or DRV8825 driver
  • 1 x 12V 30A power supply
  • 1 x PowerSupply Connector
  • 1 x Thermistor for heatbed
  • 1 x 2M 14awg cable for power supply
  • 1 x 2M 18awg cable for heatbed
  • 1 x 12V 50mm Blower fan
  • 1 x 12v 40mm fan optional for raspi3 cooling
  • 1 x 12v 80mm fan for MKS gen cooling
  • 1 x NPN Inductive sensor (doesn't need voltage devider)
  • 1 x 22awg wires for spare
  • 1 x Raspberry Pi 3 (Optional. Using pronterface)
  • 1 x Genuine E3D Hotend (Lite6 or V6)
Hardware:
  • 2 x 400mm leadscrew
  • 12 x LM10UU linear bearing
  • 1 x 100pcs M5 Nut fastener
  • 2 x Flexible coupling
  • 1 x 1.75 PTFE tube
  • 1 x GT2 belt and GT2 20t gear
  • 2 x GT2 20 Teeth pulley
  • 1 x MK7 extruder gear
  • 1 x 608ZZ bearing
  • 1 x 2020 corner joint
  • 1 x 2020 L Connector
  • 2 x Levelling screw
  • 1 x PC4-M6 push fit connector
Screw and Nut
  • 100pcs M5x10mm button head screw
  • 20pcs M5x8mm button head screw
  • 50pcs M3x10mm pan head screw
  • 20pcs M3x20mm pan head screw
  • 20pcs M3x15mm or M3x14mm pan head screw
  • 5pcs M3x6mm (for extruder motor)
  • a few pcs of M3x30mm and M3x35mm
  • 50pcs or more M3 nut
  • a few pcs of M3 ring washer
  • 5pcs M4x25mm pan head screw
  • 6pcs M4x10mm or 12mm for Y carriage
  • 5pcs M4x8mm for power supply
  • 10pcs or more of M4 nut

Use 5mm MDF or 3mm aluminium plate. I use 3mm alu plate. Drill the 6 outer most hole based on the heatbed hole you have. Most important part is the back side. It must be cut, the others are optional. I cut them to reduce the weight a bit

• 30_07_2017. Edit PSU mount to V1, as Bobble991 mentioned that it was mirrored and touching the bed. Sorry... my bad :(

  • 02_07_2017. STL's here. It took about 1,5 kg of plastic. I print with PLA at 30% infill. Photos and instruction will soon follow

  • 30_06_2017. It's done!. She works flawlessly, a bit noisier than my hypercube printer. Just a few tweaks to make it more user friendly and I'll share the BOM and STL's

  • 18_06_2017. Almost done with the hardware build, Still waiting for few parts to arrive.

  • 04_06_2017. All essential parts are done. It's ready to build. Still waiting for MKS Gen board, Heat bed and Hotend to arrive.

  • 29_05_2017. Decided to go with a red color scheme. X axis and Z braces parts printed. All parts seems great! 10mm shaft fits very well, not too tight, not too loose either.

  • 27_05_2017. Aluminium has been cut to the size, they are 2x 515mm, 4x 500mm and 4x 430mm, can't wait for the other parts to arrive :D

title: Bed Leveling and Calibration Bracket for iGaging Digital Gauge

description.text:
This is a bracket for the iGaging Digital Electronic Indicator and is primarily designed for the Monoprice Select Mini. I already had this gauge and used it for calibrating my table saw and realized it would be awesome for levelling the bed of my 3D printer. Since making this, levelling the bed has been significantly easier and very fast.

The bracket attaches to the back of the indicator/dial/gauge which then clips on to the extruder rails. You can then move the bed of the front to back and then level the bed with extreme accuracy.

This bracket may be compatible with other gauges but these are the two that I know work.

The Gauge it connects to: https://www.amazon.com/iGaging-35-0928-Digital-Saw-Gauge/dp/B00AQGLB1K
Another Compatible Gauge: https://www.amazon.com/iGaging-35-128-Digital-Electronic-Indicator/dp/B002PTUXRO

EDIT: I updated this gauge holder so that I can clip it on with it in the HOME position. I also added a support so that when it clips on to the rail the bottom rail is held more firmly. It also now works with the rail guard in place and with it removed.

Notes:

For best results scale cup until you get satisfying fit.
If you get problem with proper fitting between main connector parts, firstly check female connector. Small indentation which orients connectors may be too shalow. Best solution for this problem will be to heat up part and use 3 or 4mm drill to reform indentation. If problem is on male connector and tooth skip, tray to scale up this part.

Prepare gold pins and glue them together. 4 pin one's got in middle and two 3 pin long on each side. Pull cable thru connectors (put cup before male connector) and prepare wires for soldering then solder prepare earlier gold pins. Connect both sides together and pull printed parts then scue cup. Optionaly use small zip tie to secure cup and provent it from sliding from male connector (small holes can be use for that). Use same ot glue to secure conection and pay attention to properly space connectoes (it may be easier to glue one side, then conect everyfing together before gluing other).
Tip: Check your connections before gluing.

I modified the PSU to have the power supply cable exit the rear of the PSU through a grommet I mounted in the rear of the aluminium case. This is fairly easy to do but be warned you will need to open a mains level PSU with potentially lethal voltages. I do not take any responsibility for you burning your house down or killing yourself and others!

You've been warned.

Anyway, all in all it goes together really neatly and is extremely handy.

I stumbled upon a pair of these back in high school and was totally blown away. Then bought a brand new pair in my early 20's and kept them for over 20 years, loved everything about them except moving them. I had an afternoon to kill so this is what I have to show for it.
I will state it right up front "These are not to scale". This is the best I can recall ( at 52 years old I don't recall much) but these are a close approximation. They are 68mm tall, 50mm wide and 50mm deep which is about 2 1/2 inches tall by about 2 inches wide by 2 inches deep.
Perfect for the desk top, I guarantee there is at least 1 person at your work that will do a double take just for the "neato factor" . ( when I was young, if you saw something you liked you would say "that is neat" ) . Anyway, I printed them with wood filament and they turned out really neat. Position them facing up to print, I added a support in the back from the Horn driver magnet to the rear that can be removed after printed. Yes, the mid range and tweeter horns can be viewed from the rear just like the real ones as well as the visible parts of the folded base cabinet. This brought back some fun memories, hopefully this will make someone else smile as well. Enjoy !

description.text:
This is a simple hook that allows you to attach various items to the sides of pet cages (accessories, toys, etc.).

Few different lengths of the arm are provided, but please feel free to rescale/remix if you need different sizes. The length of the horizontal part has been designed to fit between the bars for installation, and then rest on 4 different bars to divide the load evenly.

Those are designed to perfectly fit on the bars of small pet cages with 0.5 inch spacing (which is standard for smaller pets, like hamsters, gerbils, guinea pigs, ferrets, etc.).

Enjoy! :)

For more interesting projects, please visit my blog:
http://www.BogdanBerg.com/

Use higher infill for more strength.

You can also make them thicker, if desired.
Just try to avoid scaling it height-wise, as this may cause it to no longer fit between the cage bars.

Those are strong enough to mount some accessories (inside or outside the cage). I designed them while working on an IoT hamster wheel tracker, to mount the complete device outside of the cage (see my blog for more details: http://www.BogdanBerg.com/).

This is a drawer bracket for a dresser drawers that I got from Walmart a while back. The brackets broke so measured what was left and modeled the replacements in Fusion 360. They are slightly larger in all measurements but the holes were placed in same location to be direct replacements. They are only larger by about 2mm in all directions but are functionally identical and caused no issues when fitted.

Phone stand that mounts to CD player. My Nexus 6P (with thin case) fits perfectly in this stand. It also fits well into the CD opening on my 2004 Silverado.

Your results may vary

We all know how much hamsters love to run! They can spend the whole nigh on their wheels, and not all wheels are quiet enough to allow us humans to sleep without disruptions... :)

I tried few different wheels, and found that the "Silent Spinner" works well:
https://www.amazon.com/Love-Hamster-Wheel-8-3Inches-Removable/dp/B017SONKSY/

However, through the night, the wheel can get misplaced (especially if it's placed on a soft surface, i.e. carefresh) and result in the wheel hitting side of the cage or other elements of hamster furniture.

Worse of all, it may even fall on your hamster and scare him/her...

This is why I designed this mount:

  • it can be mounted between the bars of most popular cages (spacing between bars: 0.5 inch),
  • it's sturdy, won't wiggle and cause additional noise,
  • it supports different wheel heights (depending on the depth of your base, your wheel may be mounted higher or lower)
  • it's easy to quickly remove the wheel for cleaning - just slide it to the side and it comes right off,
  • and most of all - it will keep the wheel stable in place, so your happy hamster can be training for that next marathon!

Note that this design works perfectly with the 8.3" wheel, it won't work with smaller sized wheel, and may or may not work with larger (I haven't tried have the 12" inch one). I find the 8.3" size best for Syrian Hamsters.

You'll need zip ties to mount it to the cage.

Enjoy!

And please share a photo of your happy hamster if you make one of those :)

For more interesting projects, please visit my blog:
http://www.BogdanBerg.com/

title: Car Stereo Dash Mounting Kit for JVC KW-R920BTS KW-R925BTS in 1995-2010 Ford Econoline

description.text:
This is the installation kit I designed to install my JVC KW-R925BTS Double DIN stereo into my RV which is built on a 2008 Ford Econoline chassis.
I wasn't satisfied with the Metra Dash kit which came with my radio, so I designed this one for a more stock looking fit.

Installation Notes:

  1. After removal of the old stereo, the bottom lip of the opening for the stereo needs to be shaved down. It'll be obvious when you try to install the stereo.
  2. You'll need to print 2 of the "radiostop" pieces (1 for each side of the radio). One should be printed normal, the other needs to be printed as a mirrored version.
  3. I printed the "radiobezel" with the back side on the bed. Then I sanded the face for a smooth finish.

Notes:

Installation Notes:

  1. After removal of the old stereo, the bottom lip of the opening for the stereo needs to be shaved down. It'll be obvious when you try to install the stereo.
  2. You'll need to print 2 of the "radiostop" pieces (1 for each side of the radio). One should be printed normal, the other needs to be printed as a mirrored version.
  3. I printed the "radiobezel" with the back side on the bed. Then I sanded the face for a smooth finish.

comments.text: Hi Decyg, I've found my optimal printing sweet spot for ABS on my Wanaho I3 200 x 200 bed with a 4mm nozzle is 0.2 Primary layer  75% 1st layer height 0.2 width, 3 layers top - side and shells, 20% infill. I also have a skirt at 0.0 with layers at 4 and 8 outlines so it helps hold down the print and stops warping. Easy enough to peel off once the print is complete. I also have it in an enclosure ( Helps reduce delamination ) and I use Simplify 3D. I could possible run off a GCode if you want to give me your printer specifications to try. All youd have to do is ensure you have the bed leveled. Oh I also have a heated glass bed which I smear Elmers PVA glue stick spread over it with 3 lite criss crossing motions. Hope this helps cheers Jace

title: LCD Display for 3D printers
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This simple enclosure is to hold my Gadgets3D LCD panel for my Prusa i£ steel derivative.

It is attached to the frame with magnets or a clip over the steel frame.

It also has three 3mm LED holes - these are for LEDs I use to monitor the heated bed and two extruders (they are attached across the power to these 3 so that I can get a visual indication of the power to them).

See http://reprap.org/wiki/RAMPS_1.3/1.4_GADGETS3D_Shield_with_Panel for the panel I use.

author: mistergoomba

description.text:
have several EMAX SimonSeries 12A ESC's that I want to use in a small RC watercraft and was interested in any "how-to's" about waterproofing the ESC ... as it appears that the ESC is the component of an airborne (or waterborne) that is the most susceptible to water damage ... most solutions involve imbedding the ESC in heatshrink or a conformal coating, however, these techniques offer no method for heat dissipation ... so it was neccesary to develope one

I already had the ESC's ... then found 22mm x22mm x10mm anodized aluminum heatshinks on Amazon (Gadgeteer 10pcs Aluminum Heatsink, $8.99 for 10) ... the 3D printed parts were printed in PETG on a Makerbot 2X ... the factory heatshrink was removed from the ESC and the aluminum heatsink was attached to the surfaces of the I.C.'s utilizing the double-sided thermal transfer tape that came with the heatsinks ... the heatsink/ESC assembly was fitted into the 3D printed case with the heatsink fins protruding through the hole ... the gap around the heatsink (and the wire feed throughs) and the case, was sealed with epoxy ... the cover was fitted with a piece of foam wedged internally, between to back of the board and the cover ... and the seam was sealed with epoxy

I've only bench tested the wateproofed ESC ... and at full load, the fins of the heatsink barely get warm ... I have yet to install it in an aircraft, however ... my intent is to install this sealed ESC into a small seaplane ...

we'll see how it works off the lake this summer

remixed_from.title: Natural Ergonomic Logitech M570 Trackball Stand

description.text:
I Remixed Foxpup's mount to tweak a few things:

  1. The base is now an extrusion of the outer vertices
  2. I eliminated most of the lower brim save for the parts that contact the mouse
  3. a few things have been resized for fitment

The 45 degree mount also has a flared bottom for stability.

I included 20, 25, 30, and 45 degree mounts, but more can be generated from the blender file (which you will have to do if you want to play with z rotation of the tent). for more instructions see the 'How I designed this' section.

Resin casts

I've been expirementing with silicone molding, send me a message if you want a resin cast of this print!

Designing a new angle from the blender file

You need to:

  1. Rotate the base however much you like in the negative x direction
  2. Hit view -> bottom and make sure 'limit selection to visible' is turned on.
  3. Use 'b' to switch to boundary select mode and select all vertices you can see from the bottom.
  4. Switch back to left or right view, extrude and constrain the extrusion to the z axis (I had to hit it twice for some reason) and place the extrusion well below the rest of the model.
  5. To flatten out the bottom hit scale, then type z then 0 to put all vertices of the extrusion on the same z plane.
  6. Bring the bottom back up close to the rest of the model and you're done!

Standard fidget spinner shape, designed to be printed in vase / spiral mode, inspired by Whosawhatsis's quick print bearing. I made this for printing at the Bay Area Maker Faire today (May 20, 2017), in the Bay Area Reprap Booth. Between printing all day and a bunch printed the night before, I think I gave away almost a hundred of these.

Coincidentally I met Whosawhatsis there today. He's working what looks like is going to be an awesome little printer he calls the Cranestyle Mini.

Print with a 0.5mm extrusion width. The example prints were printed at a 0.125mm layer height and the speed set to 100mm/sec (though it was probably acceleration limited to a slower speed, total print time at those settings was 7-8 minutes). I was able to get prints down to about 3 minutes but didn't like the thick layers.

This design uses thin cuts to make it print in vase mode, may not work in all slicers (I'm using Simplify3D). There are a few welding cuts, to attach the inner wall to the outer wall, and stitching cuts to strengthen some of the joined walls.

Uses standard 608 skate bearings, available at banggood* and amazon*, printed with Atomic Filament PLA. The colors comes out quite a bit different in thin wall prints like this significantly lighter than when printing solid.

I find it easiest to assemble by inserting the outer bearings first, pressing against the inside spring to insert them, then adding the center bearing last. There are small retaining ridges that makes the bearing harder to insert, but helps to hold them in place.

description.text: for those who have no other way to check their TOM w/ MK7 extruder bed for being level

Print out the the two plates. drill out the 3mm holes and insert a 3mm screw. find a compression spring to load into the hole in the main body. this pushes down on the arm. You could also cheat with a rubber band used on the other end- any way to get down pressure  on the right hand side of the arm.Break the tabs off of the arm that are at the end, they are there to  keep the arm down on your build platform. once assembled, place the index, the funy thing with the dash marks on it, on the z platform all the way to the right side. Next slip the body and arm over the extruder mounting plate , wth one clip to each side of the motor.
To use:
Heat your bed to working temp.
Using yur control panel, lower your z axis until the reader nub on the arm hits the bed and the arm raises a little. 
Move your bed until the nub is in a corner. set your jogs to 50mm and move to another corner.
if you are using a three scew adjustment (you should) then level between the two corners then do centerline front to back.
The index is notactually calibrated to anything, but the end of the arm is 20 times farther out from the axis then the nub, so a .005 chnge at the nub equals a .1 change at the end of the arm. All that you are looking for is no motion in the end of arm. 
Worked on the machine that i tried it on. I trued it with my machinists gauge, and this one said flat. I skewed the bed and this set-up showed it out. when leveled carefully with this, it came in looking fine when double checked again with the fancy gauge. hoe this works for you well enough.

remixed_from.author: deckingman
remixed_from.title: Parametric bottle tray for small e-liquid/paint/nail varnish bottles

description.text:
A customizable bottle tray with the bottles tightly packed. I use this in my fridge. The syrup bottle i keep their always fell over, and are neatly kept in place now with this thing.

It works great for all kind of cylindrical things, such as rechargeable batteries, not just bottles. I added STLs for 13 or 23 AA or AAA batteries each.

This is loosely based on Ian Pegg’s bottle tray, and uses Tomas Ebringer’s idea to add holes.

The main difference is that this arranges the bottles on a hexagonal grid. So the holes between the bottles are smaller. The wall directly between the bottles is made as thin as possible, just barely separating the bottles. You can also give the tray a honeycomb look, using hexagonal instead of circular cross sections.

Printer:

GeeetTech i3 pro C

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

300 µm

Notes:

This should be an easy print.
I would use enough shells (2–3) that you don’t get any infill.
You may have to rotate it by 45° around the z axis to make it fit on the build platform. Or use fewer or smaller bottles.
Check out the github folder for the design history.

Allows a webcam (Microsoft Lifecam VX-3000 in this case) to be mounted to the X carriage for recording prints. For example: http://youtu.be/KM6d3yrotqw The camera sucks and there is a fair amount of sway as the carriage moves. I think the next attempt will be to attach to the Z carriage.

• Print
  • Detach X carriage from Thing-o-Matic
  • Mark drill locations by placing mount against underside of the carriage but on the outside (see photo).
  • Drill 1/8" hole in marked locations.
  • Use M3 16 (or so) bolts and nuts to secure mount.
  • Detach the cheap base from the cheap webcam and use the same screw to attach it to the mount.
  • Loop the USB cable around mount to reduce pull from the cable.
  • Replace the X carriage in the Thing-o-Matic (note this could be done before 6 also).
  • Hook up the camera to your favourite recording software and start a print!

author: sepp974

title: Tevo Tarantula Dual Stepper Inverted Z

description.text:
Made for the TEVO Tarantula but can be used with any T-Slot/V-Slot extrusions. Platform height is 5mm and will work in conjunction with parts like these: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2039503.

I use this carriage (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1839201). For the original or other horizontal arrangements, see the remixes listed below.

Designed for use with 48mm Nema 17 steppers. If you use a different size motor, you may want to adjust the posts on the base sections.

The little holes on the top of the oldham couplers are to make applying lubrication easier.

The Oldham middle sections require support, the rest can print as is. Sand the oldham sliding sections to 600 grit using water paper. Also, note the way the lead screw nuts are mounted in the rendering, this stops them from butting against the flexible couplers at the lowest point.

Place 608zz bearings in the brackets to guide the Z screw.

Firmware (Marlin):

configuration.h
Set this true
#define INVERT_Z_DIR true

configuration_adv.h
Uncomment the following
#define Z_DUAL_STEPPER_DRIVERS

The other brackets are here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2377413

If you are using the original horizontal carriage, the following remixes allow for that:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2383857
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2388589
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2408107

and for the shorter Tevo steppers this provides a bit more support:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2386472

description.text:
Due to the expensive angular interdental toothbrushes sold in Spain, I've made an adapter for the straight version, which are cheaper. It's made for the Auchan brand, in Alcampo supermarkets. You only need to cut the wire of the brush using a scissors and then insert it in the hole of the adapter, it fits with the sufficient presure.
When it breaks you can extract it and cut another brush, and you can keep using the same handle.
This solution involve an interesting save of 6€ per month.

comments.text:
I have made masks in meshmixer.
this is the easiest workflow I found.
first do a hollow. adjust the settings until you get the thickness of the shell you want.
then do a plane cut to remove the bottom
save the head at this point.
if you want to cut the eyeholes in meshmixer, you will need a "cutter" that you can use to Boolean cut the holes.
I am not sure what you are used to modeling with , but remember you can always clean up the cut with a file so better to err on the side of leaving too much than cutting more than you want.
if you need to print in sections, plane cut the sections .
you can then put multiple sections (nestled like spoons) on the same plate to print a few at a time.

title: Key Hanger Cloud Design with Magnet easy assembly

description.text:
•?((¯°·..• CLOUD KEY HANGER •..·°¯))؟•

Very cool Keyholder for hanging keys on the wall!

Insturction:

For the Assembly you need 4 Magnets, i used 4 Neodym Magnets N52 (20mm x 3mm).
Glue with Hotglue or Glue that works with PLA. Also other powerful Magnets should work fine.

For the construction you need 4 Screws (2), 2 to screw on the wall(double sided tape works too!) and 2 for the Front Part.
Small Screw 16mm should work fine, also a little bigger ones work too. (Both M3)

NOW NEW:
Easy to print Cover! Print with 0% Infill and just put it on!
++++
Fast Printtime!

Post your pictures! :)

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Clone

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

20

Notes:

EASY TO PRINT
EASY TO ASSEMBLY
:))

How did i design this?

for the Cloud i used Adobe Illustrator to make the perfect looking shape,

then i imported the 2D data to Tinkercad to make it 3D, the backpart was fully designed in tinkercad, Easy design but looks awesome!

title: FT Gremlin - Eachine TX01 mount for TJ frame

description.text:
Updated: new version of the mount, now with 15 degree angle and camera sits a little higher to have a little space between the top plate and the antenna. Also added a little "hook" to hold the camera in place.

This is a camera mount for TJ's Gremlin Frame. Designed for the Eachine TX01, may fit other cameras with same dimensions (untested!). It's angled 10 degrees. Should be a tight fit to hold the camera by friction.

Printer:

P3Steel Toolson MK2 (mod.)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20%

Screw threads

Screw a regular M3 screw through all the holes to make a thread, then use the nylon screws that came with TJ's frame to screw it to the frame.

title: S500 carbon fiber landing gear mount

description.text:
I made this for using a spare tarot 650 landing gear i had laying arround on my s500 quadcopter.It fits tight so no need for glue ,this way you can remove the legs if needed.You can add glue to them in order to get a permanent join.Its made for a 16 mm x 14mm carbon fiber tube.
45º angle between legs for better stability.
Made in PLA
If nedded i will increase the wall thickness for the tube support.

Anet A8

Supports:

No

0.1-0.2

20

Notes:

Some sanding is required if your printer leaves some material inside the main hole.
For attaching use M3 screws and nuts

title: Flashforge Creator Pro 2016 Another Spool Holder

description.text:
Flashforge Creator Pro 2016 Another Spool Holder

Update 2017 05 21 afternoon:
Added : Bearing support + Stop movement
There is not a lot of friction between the filament holder and the axe, but I wanted to use my bearings.
bearing.support.stl is for a 12mm bearing with a flanged outer ring

Stop.move.stl is a system to lock the filament holder on the axe

I don’t like the spool holder of the FlashForge Creator Pro 2016.
Depending of the filaments manufacturer, it’s difficult to have a smooth rotation.
I have tested many different systems and now I use mine.
It works with big and small filament holes.

No support needed for this system!

Just insert an aluminium tube with an 8 mm diameter.
For the lenght, it depends of your filaments, but 10cm seems to be enough.

I need also:

  • 4 screws M3x16mm (cone shaped under the head)
  • 1 Aluminium Round Tube 8mm (size 1m = 3 euros)

author: sanderto

description.text:
A new design that builds on my older spherical table cloth weights. Some users said those were too light, so here comes 50% more weight (e.g. 6 x 3/8 in balls). Also some users said the clamp mechanism was too weak and the weights could fall off. Thus here an improved mechanical clamp, with some little teeth. Does not damage the table cloth, but has some real bite ;-)

The clamp is a remix of SC2014's clamp, adapted to this use.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2 Extended

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

normal

Infill:

20%

Notes:

It prints well with fast or normal printing, no print bed adhesion issues. No need for supports.
The teeth and their respective hollow opposites can be slightly connected. But a forceful opening of the clamp with manual force makes them unstuck.

description.text:
Designed to increase the stiffness of the lower part of the Anet A8 frame and to provide a fix down location behind the Z motors, removes the movement here and gives a firm foundation for any upper frame stiffening mods. This will not fit if you have your power supply and or motherboard installed on the frame as standard.

Designed in Fusion 360, sliced with S3D, printed using no supports or rafts but I did use a brim to hold it flat a but shouldn't really be needed. Used Ice Filament PLA 1.75 subtle gray Around 4.5 hours print time each piece.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Clone

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

25%

Notes:

25% Infill, fast honeycomb 0.2 layer height, top, bottom and outline/perimeter shells set to 3.

You may need to clean the holes, I suggest a 3.5mm drill bit as this will give some fitting tolerance. All holes apart from 2 are already in the Anet A8 frame, the extra holes need to be drilled through the acrylic frame. You will need to replace the standard M3 Screws with some longer ones, 22mm long worked for me. Fit the bracket and then use it as a guide for drilling the extra holes. Be careful as when drilling acrylic the drill can catch and crack it. If you use a good sharp bit and not too much pressure drilling it shouldn't be an issue.

title: Filament runout sensor case and cleaner

description.text:
This is a clip-on body that holds the runout sensor (endstop switch) for an E3D full metal pro flex extruder from tevo tarantula.
First you clip the body onto the metal, than put the endstop into the body and finally you can clip on the cover.
The cover is easily removable so I can switch the sensor from extr1 to extr2 depending which one needs it.
Cut the foam piece a bit bigger than the holder, it has some gripper edges so it is contained.

In marlin:
config.h: enable the runoutsensor by removing the "//" before this:
-#define FILAMENT_RUNOUT_SENSOR

than in the pinRAMPS.h:
blank out the Z_MAX_PIN by adding the "//":
-#define Y_MIN_PIN 14
-#define Y_MAX_PIN 15
-#define Z_MIN_PIN 18
-//#define Z_MAX_PIN 19

go down this .h file where the actual runout is defined and change the pin to 19
-#define FIL_RUNOUT_PIN 19

Tevo Tarantula

comments.text:
so what I ended up doing was going to pinRAMPS.h
there I blanked out the Z_MAX_PIN which is defined on pin 19, than I went down in this file and changed the RUNOUT pin from 4 to 19.
In config.h I set the FIL_RUNOUT_INVERTING to true since the endstop I'm using is working like that.
